105
00:06:12.524 --> 00:06:16.294
So as a medical student, we have to study different subjects, and one of the

106
00:06:16.384 --> 00:06:20.344
subjects is obstetrics, where I learn about how when a woman is

107
00:06:20.404 --> 00:06:24.344
pregnant, she'll like to know about the health of the baby, including

108
00:06:24.404 --> 00:06:25.574
the genetic health.

109
00:06:26.504 --> 00:06:30.444
But at that time, if we want to test the chromosomes or DNA of

110
00:06:30.524 --> 00:06:34.383
the baby, we have to stick a long needle into uterus

111
00:06:34.444 --> 00:06:36.804
and to obtain some samples through amniocentesis.

112
00:06:37.484 --> 00:06:41.264
But every time we do that, there's a risk that we may harm the baby.

113
00:06:42.024 --> 00:06:45.164
So as a young medical student, I was thinking, is it possible I could actually

114
00:06:45.284 --> 00:06:49.224
avoid all of that by developing a relatively non-invasive blood test

115
00:06:49.764 --> 00:06:52.224
I can actually take from the blood of the pregnant mother?

116
00:06:53.804 --> 00:06:57.674
So I was thinking, is it possible that during pregnancy, a fetus would release its

117
00:06:57.724 --> 00:06:59.504
cells in the bloodstream of mother?

118
00:07:00.384 --> 00:07:04.094
But the question is, of course, if there are such cells, how do you know it's

119
00:07:04.144 --> 00:07:05.104
actually from the fetus?

120
00:07:06.024 --> 00:07:09.864
Then I thought, well, if the baby is a boy, then at that juncture, we

121
00:07:09.964 --> 00:07:13.664
should be able to see male cells circulating in the mother's blood.

122
00:07:14.564 --> 00:07:18.504
So I managed to persuade some professor in Oxford to actually

123
00:07:18.514 --> 00:07:22.424
allow me to do that, and for example, we can then use in situ

124
00:07:22.444 --> 00:07:26.424
hybridization, and you can see that here with the probe, every

125
00:07:26.484 --> 00:07:29.084
time we see male cells, we can see a black dot.

126
00:07:29.564 --> 00:07:33.424
So you can clearly see that in the blood of this pregnant mother, there's a number

127
00:07:33.444 --> 00:07:35.144
of male cells circulating around.

128
00:07:36.044 --> 00:07:39.984
On the other hand, every time we have to do that, then I thought it was relatively

129
00:07:40.044 --> 00:07:43.274
tedious. So I like something which is relatively

130
00:07:44.204 --> 00:07:48.164
automated, so to speak. So at that time, the polymerase chain reaction is

131
00:07:48.224 --> 00:07:52.044
just coming into existence. So I was thinking, well, maybe we can

132
00:07:52.104 --> 00:07:55.684
actually use Y chromosome PCR to detect this fetal

133
00:07:55.724 --> 00:07:56.104
DNA.

134
00:07:57.214 --> 00:08:01.064
And then this result in this publication in The Lancet, just in the year when I

135
00:08:01.144 --> 00:08:02.584
qualify as a doctor.

136
00:08:03.464 --> 00:08:04.004
And then a few

137
00:08:04.884 --> 00:08:08.614
months later, actually, The Lancet published an editorial called "Is It a

138
00:08:08.704 --> 00:08:12.624
Boy?" Because theoretically, you can use this technology to tell the sex

139
00:08:12.684 --> 00:08:16.584
of a baby. And then I graduate and became a junior doctor

140
00:08:16.904 --> 00:08:20.664
for one year. But during that time, I was constantly thinking about

141
00:08:20.724 --> 00:08:24.314
this area because I thought that somehow I've started it, and so I've

142
00:08:24.384 --> 00:08:28.144
responsibility to finish it. And so after one year,

143
00:08:28.244 --> 00:08:32.064
decide to actually go back to Oxford and actually try to do on this

144
00:08:32.124 --> 00:08:35.544
full-time. So it is a picture of myself as a PhD student in

145
00:08:35.624 --> 00:08:39.164
Oxford. I can see that I'm sort of all cover up because

146
00:08:39.544 --> 00:08:41.764
I'm actually using a male chromosome as a marker.

147
00:08:41.845 --> 00:08:44.504
Now, of course, every cell in my body have a male chromosome.

148
00:08:44.824 --> 00:08:47.404
So I try to protect my samples from myself.

149
00:08:48.724 --> 00:08:51.164
Now, but sometimes in life, if you do something

150
00:08:52.544 --> 00:08:55.584
part-time just for fun, you see all the good things about it.

151
00:08:56.204 --> 00:08:59.914
But on the other hand, if you do something full-time, then suddenly all the

152
00:09:00.004 --> 00:09:02.864
problems surface, and this is one of those fields.

153
00:09:02.924 --> 00:09:06.634
So when I start working on this full-time, I realize that even though they are

154
00:09:06.634 --> 00:09:10.584
circulating fetal cells, the concentration is really super low.

155
00:09:11.044 --> 00:09:13.923
It's like trying to hunt for this needle in a haystack.

156
00:09:14.604 --> 00:09:18.504
So after three and a half years of work, I was not able to actually get

157
00:09:18.524 --> 00:09:22.284
a system which is robust enough to be working in a clinic,

158
00:09:23.024 --> 00:09:26.964
and so my grants has finished. So at that time, the science didn't go

159
00:09:27.024 --> 00:09:30.244
well, but luckily, I was able to actually met my wife.

160
00:09:30.684 --> 00:09:34.504
So the two of us graduate together in July in

161
00:09:34.524 --> 00:09:37.804
1994, and I went back to become a doctor

162
00:09:38.524 --> 00:09:42.464
for a few years. And then 1997 came, so that was the year that Hong

163
00:09:42.524 --> 00:09:44.564
Kong went back to sovereignty of China.

164
00:09:45.124 --> 00:09:47.684
So my wife and I thought it was time to actually go home.

165
00:09:48.404 --> 00:09:51.044
So then I joined the Chinese University of Hong Kong.

166
00:09:51.084 --> 00:09:55.044
So this is a picture of our campus in the northeastern part of Hong

167
00:09:55.104 --> 00:09:55.324
Kong.

168
00:09:56.444 --> 00:10:00.124
So at that time, I was waiting actually to go back home, about three

169
00:10:00.224 --> 00:10:00.544
months.

170
00:10:01.444 --> 00:10:04.944
Then in this issue of "Nature Medicine," there were two papers

171
00:10:05.464 --> 00:10:09.184
which says that in patient with cancer, you can find cancer

172
00:10:09.224 --> 00:10:13.084
DNA in the plasma and serum of the cancer patient.

173
00:10:13.114 --> 00:10:16.944
And then suddenly, I have a strange thought, and I thought that a cancer growing in

174
00:10:16.984 --> 00:10:20.904
a patient is actually quite similar to a fetus growing in a mother.

175
00:10:21.624 --> 00:10:25.414
And also rather naively, I thought that I've actually never seen a cancer which is

176
00:10:25.464 --> 00:10:28.584
as big as an eight-pound baby. So I thought, well,

177
00:10:28.924 --> 00:10:32.564
maybe if a small cancer tumor can release enough DNA for us to

178
00:10:32.644 --> 00:10:36.024
see, then surely the fetal side, I should be able to see a signal.

179
00:10:37.474 --> 00:10:41.254
And so what that means is that in the previous eight years, I was looking the wrong

180
00:10:41.344 --> 00:10:45.184
place. So now I'm trying to hunt cell-free fetal

181
00:10:45.244 --> 00:10:47.164
DNA in the plasma of pregnant mother.

182
00:10:48.724 --> 00:10:52.284
But on the other hand, by that time, you can imagine just resigned, and I don't

183
00:10:52.364 --> 00:10:55.964
have a grant, and then I've never worked on plasma before.

184
00:10:56.104 --> 00:11:00.024
So the question is, how do you even extract this DNA from plasma?

185
00:11:01.044 --> 00:11:04.884
And then I recall after my time in various Oxbridge

186
00:11:04.964 --> 00:11:08.124
colleges, I never actually quite enjoy the food there.

187
00:11:08.744 --> 00:11:11.984
So sometimes I actually go and cook instant noodles in my room.

188
00:11:12.624 --> 00:11:15.824
And of course, to cook instant noodles, what you do is that you boil some water,

189
00:11:16.444 --> 00:11:20.064
and you put the noodles in, and then a few minutes later, you have your dinner,

190
00:11:20.184 --> 00:11:23.784
right? So I was thinking, how about if I take some of the plasma serum

191
00:11:24.324 --> 00:11:28.004
and just boil it for five minutes and take a few drops to do

192
00:11:28.054 --> 00:11:28.524
PCR?

193
00:11:29.474 --> 00:11:33.204
And you probably think that it's crazy, but sometimes if you don't have resources,

194
00:11:33.244 --> 00:11:36.804
you have to try crazy things. And indeed, this is what we've done.

195
00:11:36.844 --> 00:11:40.684
And so you can see that even with this very crude preparation, I was able to

196
00:11:40.744 --> 00:11:44.224
actually see a signal in some pregnant mother, a Y chromosome signal,

197
00:11:44.704 --> 00:11:46.564
and some of the others do not have signal.

198
00:11:47.404 --> 00:11:51.144
And later on, I find that all the ones with the Y chromosome signal all have

199
00:11:51.184 --> 00:11:54.424
baby boys, and all the one without all have baby girls.

200
00:11:54.804 --> 00:11:54.814
Oh.

201
00:11:54.844 --> 00:11:58.524
So this is the first discovery of cell-free fetal DNA in maternal plasma and

202
00:11:58.584 --> 00:12:02.364
serum. It hasn't been shown before because previously people was

203
00:12:02.444 --> 00:12:06.124
focused on sorting the cells, and plasma is stuff that they throw

204
00:12:06.184 --> 00:12:09.908
away immediately.And then later on, we find that actually this

205
00:12:09.928 --> 00:12:13.578
cell-free DNA entered maternal blood very early on, like from

206
00:12:13.728 --> 00:12:17.668
six weeks of pregnancy. And surprisingly, by the 10 weeks,

207
00:12:17.708 --> 00:12:21.508
the concentration reaches 10%, 15%, which is

208
00:12:21.608 --> 00:12:25.268
amazingly high because imagine a 10-week fetus is still super small

209
00:12:25.428 --> 00:12:26.768
compared with the size of a mother.

210
00:12:27.508 --> 00:12:31.368
And also, after delivery of the baby, the free

211
00:12:31.448 --> 00:12:35.388
DNA concentration dropped very quickly with a half-life of

212
00:12:35.448 --> 00:12:39.118
16 minutes. And as a matter of fact, so this work actually

213
00:12:39.128 --> 00:12:43.108
established the rapid kinetics of cell-free DNA, which of course now

214
00:12:43.168 --> 00:12:46.228
you see in liquid biopsy is the same thing.

215
00:12:46.888 --> 00:12:50.808
And then we thought, now we have this new source of fetal material, so maybe

216
00:12:50.828 --> 00:12:54.488
it's time to try to convert that into some form of prenatal testing.

217
00:12:55.128 --> 00:12:58.808
Now, the number one reason why pregnant women go for prenatal testing is

218
00:12:58.848 --> 00:13:02.348
because they are worried the baby may be suffering from chromosome

219
00:13:02.388 --> 00:13:06.208
disorders like Down syndrome, which is caused by the baby having an extra

220
00:13:06.228 --> 00:13:10.188
chromosome 21. So we thought, well, can I use this technology that

221
00:13:10.228 --> 00:13:10.408
way?

222
00:13:11.948 --> 00:13:15.788
Of course, normally, you try to diagnose trisomy 21, you have to take the fetal

223
00:13:15.828 --> 00:13:19.628
cells, and then you probe it. Say, in this case, you see there's a

224
00:13:19.788 --> 00:13:22.718
free chromosome 21 signal, so the baby have trisomy 21.

225
00:13:23.488 --> 00:13:27.428
But now we have a problem because in my field, I don't

226
00:13:27.448 --> 00:13:31.068
have a cell. I'm looking at DNA molecules swimming

227
00:13:31.308 --> 00:13:35.148
outside cell. So the question is, how can you actually use this

228
00:13:35.228 --> 00:13:38.928
cell-free signal to deduce what is inside this

229
00:13:39.488 --> 00:13:39.828
cell?

230
00:13:40.708 --> 00:13:43.248
So it actually took me 10 years to work out.

231
00:13:43.288 --> 00:13:45.268
So the answer actually seemed very simple.

232
00:13:45.308 --> 00:13:47.278
So imagine, let's say you have a wallet,

233
00:13:48.168 --> 00:13:52.048
and sometimes you have four coins and some of the other times you

234
00:13:52.088 --> 00:13:56.028
have three coins. And I want to know today how many coins you

235
00:13:56.088 --> 00:13:59.668
have in your wallet. So one way is to ask you to hand me your wallet.

236
00:13:59.848 --> 00:14:03.478
That would be like invasive prenatal testing, a bit

237
00:14:03.508 --> 00:14:07.268
intrusive. But another way is to ask you to stand on a

238
00:14:07.308 --> 00:14:11.068
balance. Now, theoretically, on a day when you have more money,

239
00:14:11.248 --> 00:14:12.588
you should be a little bit heavier.

240
00:14:13.308 --> 00:14:15.668
But of course, the balance has to be super precise.

241
00:14:15.808 --> 00:14:19.788
So let's say that you're 120 pounds, but with one more coin, you'll be

242
00:14:19.828 --> 00:14:23.827
120.01 pounds. So the precision of the balance

243
00:14:23.888 --> 00:14:27.548
is very important. So I calculate that actually if we

244
00:14:27.768 --> 00:14:30.908
use this, so basically we need a very accurate way to

245
00:14:30.988 --> 00:14:33.368
quantify DNA from different chromosomes.

246
00:14:33.888 --> 00:14:37.688
And we estimate that you need the precision to be like 5%.

247
00:14:38.308 --> 00:14:41.468
And this is difficult because imagine in those days, if you use

248
00:14:42.048 --> 00:14:45.688
PCR, which is a doubling process, you can tell 100

249
00:14:45.768 --> 00:14:49.328
molecules from 200, but it's very difficult to tell 100 from

250
00:14:49.508 --> 00:14:50.108
105.

251
00:14:51.048 --> 00:14:54.888
And then we thought, "Well, how about if I do it digitally?" And of

252
00:14:54.928 --> 00:14:57.588
course, remember this work was done way before the

253
00:14:58.568 --> 00:15:02.328
droplet, digital PCR, et cetera. So at this time, we're thinking, well,

254
00:15:02.888 --> 00:15:06.768
in a digital scenario, you basically, the precision of

255
00:15:06.888 --> 00:15:10.548
assay is arbitrary, depends on how many tubes you actually do.

256
00:15:11.488 --> 00:15:15.008
And so after we've done that, for the first time, we're able

257
00:15:15.088 --> 00:15:18.888
to detect directly the presence of a trisomy 21 fetus

258
00:15:19.328 --> 00:15:22.908
in the blood of a pregnant mother. So we published this in PNAS.

259
00:15:24.088 --> 00:15:27.228
But strangely, within a few weeks after I published this paper,

260
00:15:27.928 --> 00:15:30.328
another group actually published a very similar paper.

261
00:15:30.648 --> 00:15:34.448
So you can see that my paper, digital PCR, their paper, digital polymerase

262
00:15:34.508 --> 00:15:38.368
chain reaction. And also, surprisingly, the two papers were

263
00:15:38.388 --> 00:15:41.308
submitted on the same day, which is May the 9th,

264
00:15:41.668 --> 00:15:42.508
2007.

265
00:15:43.788 --> 00:15:45.608
So of course, a good thing about that is

266
00:15:46.548 --> 00:15:49.848
it's likely that this method will work because at least two groups have

267
00:15:49.928 --> 00:15:53.908
independently replicated data. But the tough bit is of course then

268
00:15:53.948 --> 00:15:57.848
we have competition. So basically, two groups are now racing to try

269
00:15:57.928 --> 00:15:59.348
to push this to the clinic.

270
00:16:00.808 --> 00:16:04.708
But then both of us, we met some problems. So what's the problem?

271
00:16:04.768 --> 00:16:08.708
Now the problem is that if you try to use PCR, let's say to measure a

272
00:16:08.768 --> 00:16:10.478
target on chromosome 21,

273
00:16:11.468 --> 00:16:15.348
but if you focus on one gene assay, but there are actually about

274
00:16:15.368 --> 00:16:19.028
150 genes on chromosome 21, you're basically ignoring all the other

275
00:16:19.068 --> 00:16:22.728
information. So the assay is not actually that robust.

276
00:16:23.368 --> 00:16:27.288
So thinking, is it possible we could have a method which will allow me to

277
00:16:27.368 --> 00:16:31.188
survey the entire genome in one go?

278
00:16:31.948 --> 00:16:35.708
And at the time, actually, the next-generation sequencing started

279
00:16:35.808 --> 00:16:39.728
coming into existence. But the first application of next-generation sequencing in

280
00:16:39.788 --> 00:16:43.508
those days are qualitative. So they're asking if this tumor

281
00:16:43.588 --> 00:16:47.548
has this mutation, yes or no. But as

282
00:16:47.648 --> 00:16:50.908
I was thinking, is it possible we could do it in a quantitative fashion,

283
00:16:51.868 --> 00:16:55.528
in a shotgun or random fashion? So let's say we randomly sequence

284
00:16:55.668 --> 00:16:59.528
millions of molecules in the blood of this pregnant woman, and then I

285
00:16:59.628 --> 00:17:03.448
find the origin of each of those, sequence.

286
00:17:03.468 --> 00:17:07.308
And then at the bottom, I can use a quantitative tally to see if any

287
00:17:07.348 --> 00:17:09.888
chromosome has over or underrepresented.

288
00:17:11.028 --> 00:17:15.008
And by doing that, we find that actually in trisomy 21 pregnancy, you can

289
00:17:15.048 --> 00:17:18.608
see the signal is actually very distinguishable from those who are

290
00:17:18.709 --> 00:17:22.668
euploid. We actually look at 28 cases, 14 with

291
00:17:22.709 --> 00:17:26.088
Down syndrome, 14 normal, and they're 100% accurate.

292
00:17:26.748 --> 00:17:28.968
So we're very excited. So we published this paper.

293
00:17:29.888 --> 00:17:33.768
And also, but very interesting, within a few weeks of this paper, the

294
00:17:33.888 --> 00:17:36.048
other guy also published their paper.

295
00:17:37.168 --> 00:17:37.178
Ah.

296
00:17:37.178 --> 00:17:38.808
And I was thinking, "Well, who is this guy?

297
00:17:38.868 --> 00:17:42.728
Why are we constantly competing each other?" So I take a

298
00:17:42.788 --> 00:17:46.688
look, and of course, you can see the last author is the name of Stephen Quake.

299
00:17:47.248 --> 00:17:51.088
So I take a look at his website and find that he's a professor of bioengineering

300
00:17:51.168 --> 00:17:54.868
from Stanford. And also very curiously, he also graduated

301
00:17:55.228 --> 00:17:55.748
from Oxford,

302
00:17:56.848 --> 00:18:00.028
in physics, and also in the same year that I graduated in '94.

303
00:18:00.768 --> 00:18:04.268
So actually, as a turnout, my wife actually studied physics in Oxford.

304
00:18:04.348 --> 00:18:07.608
So I asked her, does she know him? And she said no.

305
00:18:08.168 --> 00:18:11.768
But what she did is that she take out this photoAnd that's Steve Quake.

306
00:18:13.468 --> 00:18:16.968
So you can see it's almost like the person sitting next to you today is the one

307
00:18:16.988 --> 00:18:19.108
who's going to compete with you 10 years from now.

308
00:18:20.168 --> 00:18:23.908
And not only that, a few years later, I was fortunate enough to be elected into US

309
00:18:23.968 --> 00:18:27.828
National Academy of Science. And on the day when the result came out, I saw

310
00:18:27.868 --> 00:18:31.008
my name, and then I saw his as well. So then the

311
00:18:31.048 --> 00:18:34.988
three of us took a picture here at the induction

312
00:18:35.088 --> 00:18:35.538
ceremony.

313
00:18:36.648 --> 00:18:40.448
So anyway, back to science. So now we have this prototype method which

314
00:18:40.508 --> 00:18:44.388
seems to be very robust in detecting trisomy 21 from the

315
00:18:44.448 --> 00:18:48.368
mother's blood. And then the next thing is to push out in the clinical practice,

316
00:18:48.428 --> 00:18:52.088
we need a clinical trial. So I spent the next three years doing, and this is the

317
00:18:52.108 --> 00:18:55.708
result. You can see on the right-hand side is a signal from trisomy 21

318
00:18:55.728 --> 00:18:59.068
pregnancy, and on the left are the normal pregnancy.

319
00:18:59.428 --> 00:19:01.868
And basically, the test is over 99% accurate.

320
00:19:02.408 --> 00:19:03.508
So we thought we're ready.

321
00:19:04.768 --> 00:19:08.648
But of course, I couldn't do that in the university.

322
00:19:09.268 --> 00:19:13.128
If I want to commercialize this, I have to work with some companies.

323
00:19:13.548 --> 00:19:17.248
And also at that time in Hong Kong, it's not very common for

324
00:19:17.288 --> 00:19:19.188
professors to have their own companies.

325
00:19:19.708 --> 00:19:21.568
So we thought, "Well, how about licensing?"

326
00:19:22.468 --> 00:19:25.288
Of course, when you talk about licensing, the company will say, "Well, do you have

327
00:19:25.348 --> 00:19:29.308
patents?" And so we've been learning how to file patents for the last

328
00:19:29.528 --> 00:19:33.188
20 years. But for the first one, we weren't really that experienced.

329
00:19:33.248 --> 00:19:36.608
So my university actually licensed it to a company based in the UK.

330
00:19:37.568 --> 00:19:40.588
And that company sat on it and thought it was useless.

331
00:19:41.008 --> 00:19:44.348
So thought it was rubbish and gave it back to the university, which actually turned

332
00:19:44.388 --> 00:19:48.048
out to be a very big mistake because this patent for subsequently was very

333
00:19:48.068 --> 00:19:48.578
valuable.

334
00:19:49.868 --> 00:19:52.468
And then, so I have to find another person who's interested.

335
00:19:52.708 --> 00:19:56.618
So I remember I went to Thailand for a genetic conference and

336
00:19:56.628 --> 00:20:00.148
then met this gentleman who is Dr. Charles Cantor, who at that

337
00:20:00.228 --> 00:20:03.628
time was the chief scientific officer of a company called Sequenom.

338
00:20:04.628 --> 00:20:08.528
So we start talking and then collaborating and eventually, actually,

339
00:20:08.548 --> 00:20:10.668
Sequenom licensed our technology.

340
00:20:11.488 --> 00:20:14.478
But on the other side, of course, you can imagine in Stanford, the professor is

341
00:20:14.488 --> 00:20:16.388
very experienced with commercialization.

342
00:20:16.988 --> 00:20:20.808
So Steve Quake actually licensed his technology to Veranara, which was

343
00:20:20.827 --> 00:20:22.068
then bought by Illumina.

344
00:20:22.888 --> 00:20:26.468
So now you can imagine on one side you have Illumina with the Stanford

345
00:20:26.608 --> 00:20:30.168
patent, on the other side, you have Sequenom with my patent.

346
00:20:30.888 --> 00:20:34.348
And so of course, they will use patent as a weapon and they fight.

347
00:20:34.428 --> 00:20:36.328
So there's a series of four lawsuits.

348
00:20:36.568 --> 00:20:39.328
So we won three of them, and they won one.

349
00:20:39.388 --> 00:20:43.268
So eventually we decide to settle out of court, and then we basically

350
00:20:43.308 --> 00:20:47.177
put all the patent into a pool, and then people who want access of this

351
00:20:47.208 --> 00:20:48.888
technology can just license from pool.

352
00:20:49.668 --> 00:20:53.378
So this technology is now called NIPT, non-invasive prenatal testing,

353
00:20:53.908 --> 00:20:57.388
which has been actually used 100 million times, now

354
00:20:57.428 --> 00:21:00.928
buy. And also it's a standard of care in the prenatal medicine.

355
00:21:02.808 --> 00:21:06.708
So now we can see how I developed this technology is because I look at

356
00:21:06.748 --> 00:21:10.468
the cancer work, and this inspired me to hunt for fetal

357
00:21:10.528 --> 00:21:12.408
cell-free DNA in maternal plasma.

358
00:21:13.008 --> 00:21:16.988
And I thought the fetal side seems to be working well, so maybe it's time for us to

359
00:21:17.068 --> 00:21:19.128
actually feed this back into cancer.

360
00:21:20.248 --> 00:21:24.008
So we started with a cancer called nasopharyngeal cancer, or NPC for

361
00:21:24.068 --> 00:21:27.728
short, which is a cancer very common in the southern part of

362
00:21:27.768 --> 00:21:28.108
China.

363
00:21:28.968 --> 00:21:32.728
For example, a Cantonese man like myself, my lifetime risk of this

364
00:21:32.748 --> 00:21:34.548
cancer is about one in 39.

365
00:21:35.608 --> 00:21:39.268
And also another reason why we choose this cancer is because for this method to

366
00:21:39.308 --> 00:21:43.048
work, I need to have a tumor-specific target which I can

367
00:21:43.168 --> 00:21:46.147
use, just like the Y chromosome from baby boy.

368
00:21:46.628 --> 00:21:50.568
And for nasopharyngeal cancer, we have such a target in the form of Epstein-Barr

369
00:21:50.608 --> 00:21:54.408
virus DNA. So I was thinking maybe in the course of this biology, the

370
00:21:54.468 --> 00:21:58.008
NPC cell will release the EBV DNA in the bloodstream, which we can use.

371
00:21:58.618 --> 00:22:02.348
I still remember when I first proposed that, many of my colleagues don't believe

372
00:22:02.368 --> 00:22:05.968
it'll work because they thought most of us are chronic EBV carriers.

373
00:22:05.998 --> 00:22:09.148
So if you do this, it's going to have a lot of false positive.

374
00:22:09.808 --> 00:22:12.408
But interesting, when we did the experiment, we find actually it's pretty good.

375
00:22:12.468 --> 00:22:16.448
So on the left-hand side is in the plasma of NPC patient, is really stuffed

376
00:22:16.508 --> 00:22:20.168
full of EBV DNA. On the right-hand side is healthy individuals, and

377
00:22:20.248 --> 00:22:21.248
most are negative.

378
00:22:22.308 --> 00:22:26.068
Then we thought, "Well, maybe we can use this technology to screen for this

379
00:22:26.128 --> 00:22:29.548
cancer." So a few years ago, we did a large trial

380
00:22:30.168 --> 00:22:34.128
involving over 20,000 subjects in the whole territory of

381
00:22:34.168 --> 00:22:34.668
Hong Kong.

382
00:22:35.688 --> 00:22:39.518
And then we focused on the high-risk group, who are males between age

383
00:22:39.628 --> 00:22:43.508
of 40 and 60. And we want to see whether plasma EBV DNA can

384
00:22:43.548 --> 00:22:46.428
be used to screen for this cancer.

385
00:22:47.798 --> 00:22:51.468
And in the end, out of 20,000 people, we pick up 34 cases of

386
00:22:51.508 --> 00:22:54.818
cancer. Now, interestingly, you can find that without screening,

387
00:22:55.328 --> 00:22:59.238
most of the cases are stage III and stage IV, so 80% are in the late

388
00:22:59.308 --> 00:23:02.938
stage. But now in the screen cohort, you can see they now

389
00:23:03.008 --> 00:23:06.308
change to 70% in stage I and stage II.

390
00:23:06.328 --> 00:23:10.268
And because it's so early, you can see the screen cohort of the 34 people we

391
00:23:10.308 --> 00:23:13.708
screen, only one die. So the chance of dying is around

392
00:23:13.848 --> 00:23:17.528
3%. But on the other hand, if you don't screen, the chance of

393
00:23:17.608 --> 00:23:21.588
mortality is 40%. So basically, it's over a 10 times reduction

394
00:23:21.608 --> 00:23:25.248
in mortality. So this work was published in "The New England Journal of Medicine,"

395
00:23:25.628 --> 00:23:28.968
was chosen to be one of the 10 notable articles that year.

396
00:23:30.328 --> 00:23:32.308
Of course, nasopharyngeal cancer is my first goal.

397
00:23:32.928 --> 00:23:36.548
I want to be able to extend this technology to other cancer types.

398
00:23:37.088 --> 00:23:40.748
But of course, not every cancer have a virus as a target.

399
00:23:41.288 --> 00:23:44.968
So we try a number of different methods, and eventually we settle

400
00:23:45.008 --> 00:23:47.818
down on epigenetics using DNA methylation.

401
00:23:48.518 --> 00:23:52.508
So we develop a genome-wide methylation assay and show that

402
00:23:52.548 --> 00:23:56.108
for the first time that one test is enough for you to screen

403
00:23:56.508 --> 00:23:57.688
multiple types of cancer.

404
00:23:58.648 --> 00:24:02.448
And furthermore, because different organs in our body have got

405
00:24:02.468 --> 00:24:06.308
different methylation status, I can also use this technology to tell

406
00:24:06.368 --> 00:24:10.236
us where is the tumor of origin.So after we have developed

407
00:24:10.256 --> 00:24:14.036
these technologies, then I thought, well, this time we are little bit more

408
00:24:15.116 --> 00:24:17.476
mature in our commercialization experience.

409
00:24:17.896 --> 00:24:21.856
So I started together with two of my students, a company called Cerena, which stand

410
00:24:21.896 --> 00:24:25.696
for circulating nucleic acid. Basically, we're trying to develop a

411
00:24:25.756 --> 00:24:29.516
test which will allow us to detect cancer at the early stage, so we can do

412
00:24:29.556 --> 00:24:33.416
something about that. But interesting, at the same time, Illumina just

413
00:24:33.476 --> 00:24:37.116
started a company called GRAIL, and you can see the mission is very similar, to

414
00:24:37.156 --> 00:24:39.156
detect cancer early when it can be cured.

415
00:24:39.736 --> 00:24:42.516
So basically you can see that Cerena and GRAIL are going the same direction.

416
00:24:43.176 --> 00:24:46.526
So just based on my previous experience, if that happens,

417
00:24:46.956 --> 00:24:49.776
eventually we end up seeing each other in court, right?

418
00:24:50.696 --> 00:24:52.936
And so this time we try to be proactive.

419
00:24:53.116 --> 00:24:57.096
So in 2017, the two companies merged, and I become

420
00:24:57.136 --> 00:24:58.516
a scientific co-founder of GRAIL.

421
00:24:59.436 --> 00:25:03.216
And this is actually the merger party, which is the 2017

422
00:25:03.296 --> 00:25:06.696
NBA Finals. So that year, of course, the Golden State Warrior won.

423
00:25:07.296 --> 00:25:10.976
So this is in San Francisco, and the person next to me is a founding

424
00:25:11.076 --> 00:25:14.596
CEO of GRAIL, who's a guy called Jeff Huber, who's a guy who

425
00:25:14.616 --> 00:25:18.516
brought us Google Maps. And so after a few years of work, so

426
00:25:18.576 --> 00:25:22.396
basically this company launched the first multi-cancer early detection test.

427
00:25:22.936 --> 00:25:26.516
And of course, the field is hot heating up now because a number of other

428
00:25:26.576 --> 00:25:29.556
companies have entered this area, like Exact Science,

429
00:25:30.176 --> 00:25:32.356
Guardant, and many Chinese companies.

430
00:25:33.196 --> 00:25:35.056
But of course, we also have some challenges.

431
00:25:35.136 --> 00:25:38.536
For example, GRAIL has recently released in a press release

432
00:25:38.996 --> 00:25:42.856
that in a large-scale trial of 140,000 people in the UK,

433
00:25:43.476 --> 00:25:45.316
they actually missed some of the key goals.

434
00:25:46.076 --> 00:25:50.016
And so as a result, in March this year, Nature actually published this

435
00:25:50.056 --> 00:25:54.026
piece saying that, are those multi-cancer early detection

436
00:25:54.136 --> 00:25:58.036
tests ready for prime time yet? So I think more work is

437
00:25:58.096 --> 00:26:01.836
needed. So in the final part of my talk, I'm going to talk about some of the

438
00:26:01.896 --> 00:26:05.636
work that we've been doing to try to push the performance

439
00:26:05.876 --> 00:26:09.696
in this area. So if you look at DNA

440
00:26:10.056 --> 00:26:13.276
inside the cell, they're basically chromosome length, long molecules.

441
00:26:13.936 --> 00:26:17.716
But interestingly, if you look at DNA, which is in our plasma, it is

442
00:26:17.776 --> 00:26:20.236
actually fragmented into millions of pieces.

443
00:26:21.476 --> 00:26:24.876
And so for many years, people thought this fragmentation is random, but we and

444
00:26:24.936 --> 00:26:28.456
others have shown that there's actually a pattern to this fragmentation.

445
00:26:28.876 --> 00:26:32.216
So the study of this fragmentation pattern is now called cell-free DNA

446
00:26:32.356 --> 00:26:33.136
fragmentomics.

447
00:26:34.116 --> 00:26:35.956
And you can actually study a number of ways.

448
00:26:36.056 --> 00:26:38.836
For example, you can look at the size of the molecules.

449
00:26:39.556 --> 00:26:43.496
Now, for example, back to the fetal situation, if you measure

450
00:26:43.536 --> 00:26:47.396
the size of fetal DNA and the mother's DNA in the mother's blood, this is what

451
00:26:47.476 --> 00:26:51.356
you get. So the x-axis is the size of molecules, some 50 to 200

452
00:26:51.376 --> 00:26:55.076
base pair, and the y-axis is how much of those molecules you can find.

453
00:26:55.736 --> 00:26:59.456
So the fetal DNA is in blue, the total DNA, which is mainly from

454
00:26:59.516 --> 00:27:03.056
mother, is in red. So we can see the fetal DNA is a little bit

455
00:27:03.156 --> 00:27:04.956
shorter than the mother's DNA.

456
00:27:06.076 --> 00:27:10.056
Now so we can imagine that if you take a sample, the more fetal DNA it has in

457
00:27:10.076 --> 00:27:13.616
the sample, the shorter should be the size distribution.

458
00:27:13.696 --> 00:27:17.576
So what that means is that you can use the size as a metric to

459
00:27:17.596 --> 00:27:19.556
measure the concentration of fetal DNA.

460
00:27:19.916 --> 00:27:23.256
So here you can see a positive correlation between a

461
00:27:23.356 --> 00:27:27.236
size-based measurement and a genome-based measurement, which is based on

462
00:27:27.296 --> 00:27:27.916
Y chromosome.

463
00:27:28.856 --> 00:27:32.236
But of course, if you use the genome-based measurement, you can only do it if the

464
00:27:32.276 --> 00:27:36.156
baby is a boy. But now with the size base, you can do it

465
00:27:36.236 --> 00:27:38.716
irrespective of the sex of the baby.

466
00:27:38.756 --> 00:27:42.056
And actually, the concentration of fetal DNA is the number one parameters

467
00:27:42.496 --> 00:27:45.466
governing the accuracy of non-invasive prenatal testing.

468
00:27:46.556 --> 00:27:48.406
And furthermore, you can push this even further.

469
00:27:48.516 --> 00:27:51.276
Now imagine, let's say, the baby have Down syndrome.

470
00:27:51.336 --> 00:27:55.096
It has an extra copy of chromosome 21, which is pushing out the

471
00:27:55.176 --> 00:27:58.866
short DNA in the mother's plasma. So if you measure size distribution of

472
00:27:58.916 --> 00:28:02.756
chromosome 21, compare with the other chromosomes, then you can

473
00:28:02.816 --> 00:28:06.136
actually see a shortening if the baby have Down syndrome.

474
00:28:06.596 --> 00:28:10.476
So now, actually we'll do a commercial non-invasive prenatal test.

475
00:28:11.016 --> 00:28:14.796
Basically, they will combine the counting and the size measurement together.

476
00:28:16.156 --> 00:28:18.436
Then you will say, well, how about non-pregnant subjects?

477
00:28:18.496 --> 00:28:20.236
So in non-pregnant subject, this is what you get.

478
00:28:20.616 --> 00:28:24.556
You got a predominant peak, which is 160 base pair, which is

479
00:28:24.616 --> 00:28:26.876
a nucleosome size fragment.

480
00:28:27.796 --> 00:28:31.616
And then if the patient have cancer, like liver cancer, then the higher the

481
00:28:31.696 --> 00:28:35.076
cancer DNA concentration, the shorter is the size distribution.

482
00:28:35.236 --> 00:28:38.836
So once again, indicating the cancer DNA in

483
00:28:38.876 --> 00:28:41.616
circulation is shorter than the non-cancer DNA.

484
00:28:43.616 --> 00:28:47.596
Now, in addition to measurement size, you can also look at the end structure

485
00:28:47.636 --> 00:28:51.556
of the molecule, because the end could be

486
00:28:51.616 --> 00:28:55.056
maybe double-strand DNA, blunt end, or maybe jacket,

487
00:28:55.416 --> 00:28:59.176
protruding ends. So jacket-ness is one of the fragmentomics

488
00:28:59.236 --> 00:29:02.976
marker. And you can also look at the sequence at the end, we

489
00:29:03.016 --> 00:29:06.896
call end motif. So let's say you focus on the four nucleotide at

490
00:29:06.936 --> 00:29:10.716
the end of molecule. So the number possibility is four to

491
00:29:10.796 --> 00:29:14.616
power four. So in other words, by doing that, you split the cell-free DNA

492
00:29:14.676 --> 00:29:16.756
into 256 types.

493
00:29:18.976 --> 00:29:22.496
And reason we've been asking this question, is this the whole picture?

494
00:29:22.896 --> 00:29:26.206
Because you can see that after those publication, many other

495
00:29:26.416 --> 00:29:27.706
individuals have actually

496
00:29:28.536 --> 00:29:32.456
shown that you can actually use end motif, et cetera, as a type of cancer

497
00:29:32.476 --> 00:29:35.866
marker. But reason we ask, how complete is this?

498
00:29:36.316 --> 00:29:39.416
The reason is because imagine you have a double strand DNA molecule here.

499
00:29:39.876 --> 00:29:43.576
Because of the presence of jacket end, you have to do some sort of polishing

500
00:29:43.976 --> 00:29:47.636
before you can do sequencing. And by the polishing, you

501
00:29:47.816 --> 00:29:51.396
basically will extend the 3' end,

502
00:29:51.676 --> 00:29:54.716
and if there's protruding 3' end, you chop it.

503
00:29:55.296 --> 00:29:58.756
So what that means is basically the 3' end is

504
00:29:58.796 --> 00:30:02.676
artifactual. Only the 5' end is the real

505
00:30:02.736 --> 00:30:06.716
sequence. So in other words, the fragmentomics field in the literature up to

506
00:30:06.856 --> 00:30:09.396
now have all based on just the 5' end.

507
00:30:09.416 --> 00:30:13.376
The 3' end is unexplored. So reason we ask, is it

508
00:30:13.436 --> 00:30:16.776
possible for us to develop technology which will allow us to look at the 3'

509
00:30:16.976 --> 00:30:20.700
end?So we thought that one way to do that is to say that you have

510
00:30:20.800 --> 00:30:24.620
a double-strand DNA in circulation, a denature, and then

511
00:30:24.860 --> 00:30:28.360
use a single-strand library preparation method.

512
00:30:28.390 --> 00:30:31.940
And by doing that, for the first time, we'll have a native 3'

513
00:30:32.420 --> 00:30:34.260
end motif, which I can study.

514
00:30:35.360 --> 00:30:38.510
So imagine now in this situation, I have a 5' end,

515
00:30:39.300 --> 00:30:42.470
and then I have 3' end. So we need to give them some names.

516
00:30:42.940 --> 00:30:46.540
So for this one, 5' end, I call this a 5' end motif, so

517
00:30:46.700 --> 00:30:50.580
EM5, so end motif 5 prime. And now on this side,

518
00:30:50.820 --> 00:30:54.000
I call this EM3, end motif 3 prime.

519
00:30:54.740 --> 00:30:57.900
And of course, you can imagine this fragment has to be chopped off

520
00:30:58.400 --> 00:31:01.920
somewhere from a genome. So in a genome, there will be some

521
00:31:02.220 --> 00:31:05.780
sequence which is before that, so I call this pre-end motif,

522
00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:06.440
PREM.

523
00:31:07.280 --> 00:31:11.200
And then there's some bit which is at the other side, I

524
00:31:11.240 --> 00:31:13.360
call it post-end motif, POEM.

525
00:31:14.180 --> 00:31:17.220
So basically, you have these four types of new fragmentomics marker.

526
00:31:17.940 --> 00:31:21.780
So next, we like to see what happens to those marker in the plasma of

527
00:31:21.880 --> 00:31:25.300
healthy individual without cancer. And this is what happened.

528
00:31:25.360 --> 00:31:28.600
Now, for example, you look at this particular

529
00:31:28.780 --> 00:31:32.560
EM5, and here on the x-axis,

530
00:31:33.020 --> 00:31:36.680
I plot all the end motif in alphabetical order, starting with A, C,

531
00:31:36.960 --> 00:31:40.080
G, and T. And the y-axis is the frequency of

532
00:31:40.100 --> 00:31:43.180
those motif. And you can see that EM5 has

533
00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:46.780
specific features. It has an enrichment of

534
00:31:46.920 --> 00:31:50.620
CN motif. And we have previously shown that the CN motif is

535
00:31:50.680 --> 00:31:53.920
due to an enzyme called DNase 1-like 3.

536
00:31:55.540 --> 00:31:59.020
And now we look at the PREM, and you can see that the pattern is completely

537
00:31:59.060 --> 00:32:02.300
different. There's an enrichment of the T end motif.

538
00:32:03.560 --> 00:32:06.740
And the yellow side, EM3, you can see the pattern.

539
00:32:06.820 --> 00:32:09.680
There's enrichment of T, plus a bit of A and G.

540
00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:14.860
And then POEM, you can see this enrichment of C.

541
00:32:15.980 --> 00:32:17.580
So basically now you have the four types.

542
00:32:18.220 --> 00:32:21.100
Now, if you look carefully, you see something very intriguing.

543
00:32:21.140 --> 00:32:24.930
You can see that actually EM5 and POEM are very

544
00:32:25.060 --> 00:32:28.870
similar. You can see both have this enrichment of C motif, which is these two

545
00:32:28.980 --> 00:32:32.400
guys. But of course, you think about it in more detail, you can say that

546
00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:36.640
the POEM is actually a EM5 of the subsequent fragment.

547
00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:39.840
So it's actually logical that the two of them are correlated.

548
00:32:40.410 --> 00:32:43.820
And similarly, on the other side, you can see this also have similarity.

549
00:32:43.940 --> 00:32:47.360
There's an enrichment of T and also a bit of the

550
00:32:48.600 --> 00:32:48.760
A.

551
00:32:49.680 --> 00:32:53.240
And of course, you think about that, the PREM is basically a

552
00:32:53.360 --> 00:32:55.560
EM3 of the preceding fragments.

553
00:32:57.240 --> 00:33:00.240
Okay. And then we can actually plot this in a heat map.

554
00:33:00.300 --> 00:33:04.290
So on the vertical axis here is basically all the end motif sequence,

555
00:33:04.720 --> 00:33:07.120
and these are the four types of fragmentomics marker.

556
00:33:07.740 --> 00:33:11.340
And you can see, for example, the similarity of PREM and EM3, you can see,

557
00:33:11.920 --> 00:33:15.820
and similarity of EM5 and POEM. But also, when you plot it this

558
00:33:15.880 --> 00:33:19.660
way, you can also very clearly see there's also some features in which

559
00:33:19.820 --> 00:33:23.610
these two are similar, but there are some areas which are different, which we can

560
00:33:23.640 --> 00:33:25.080
actually explore in the future.

561
00:33:27.340 --> 00:33:30.740
And just now, when I talk about size, I said if you do a

562
00:33:30.800 --> 00:33:34.700
double-strand DNA library preparation, you have this 160 base

563
00:33:34.780 --> 00:33:38.380
pair, which is nucleosomal peak. But now, if you try to use a

564
00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:41.160
single-strand library preparation, you actually have two peaks.

565
00:33:41.560 --> 00:33:45.220
One is in 160, and the other one is curiously at a

566
00:33:45.480 --> 00:33:46.200
50 base pair.

567
00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:51.980
And now, basically, I can separately look at the fragmentomic

568
00:33:52.040 --> 00:33:55.280
markers for the 50 base pair peak and also

569
00:33:55.380 --> 00:33:58.860
160. So you can basically see the four type of marker, PREM,

570
00:33:58.980 --> 00:34:02.900
EM5, EM3, and POEM for these two. So the message

571
00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:06.620
we see is that you can see, for example, in the larger peak, the

572
00:34:06.660 --> 00:34:10.571
demarcation is very sharp. But here in the lower peak, it's less sharp.

573
00:34:11.060 --> 00:34:14.980
Probably means that as the DNA got degraded more and more, basically, all

574
00:34:15.040 --> 00:34:18.720
this, the more and more process got involved, and so they become

575
00:34:18.761 --> 00:34:19.180
fussier.

576
00:34:20.740 --> 00:34:24.060
And then next question you ask, how about can I use those type of

577
00:34:24.321 --> 00:34:27.060
fragmentomic markers for cancer liquid biopsy?

578
00:34:27.841 --> 00:34:30.190
So basically, what we've got now, we have this four series.

579
00:34:30.560 --> 00:34:33.821
So look at individual with liver cancer and without liver cancer.

580
00:34:34.341 --> 00:34:38.261
And now we plot volcano plot for each of these four classes of fragmentomic

581
00:34:38.321 --> 00:34:42.180
markers. And the red ones are the over-represented in liver cancer,

582
00:34:42.620 --> 00:34:45.301
and the blue one are under-represented in cancer.

583
00:34:45.640 --> 00:34:49.240
You can clearly see that you can use that as a cancer liquid biopsy

584
00:34:49.301 --> 00:34:49.670
marker.

585
00:34:50.761 --> 00:34:54.500
And then here is showing a series of area under the

586
00:34:54.560 --> 00:34:58.480
ROC curve, in which you can see that by combining different

587
00:34:58.540 --> 00:35:02.319
amount, you actually have gradual increase in diagnostic performance.

588
00:35:04.460 --> 00:35:07.460
So up to now, I've shown you a number of new fragmentomics marker.

589
00:35:08.120 --> 00:35:11.680
And recently, we also ask, is this the whole pattern, whole picture?

590
00:35:12.220 --> 00:35:15.950
The reason why I say that is because you can imagine you have a double strand DNA

591
00:35:15.980 --> 00:35:19.700
molecule in the circulation floating around, and they have them

592
00:35:19.800 --> 00:35:23.760
sequencing method. But all of the sequencing method have one thing in

593
00:35:23.800 --> 00:35:27.080
common, is that the Watson and Crick strand are separated,

594
00:35:27.900 --> 00:35:31.300
and then basically, you lost the connection information.

595
00:35:31.710 --> 00:35:35.420
It's almost like you have a pair of gloves, and you put into a washing machine,

596
00:35:35.960 --> 00:35:38.800
and basically, the washing machine will wash those gloves separately.

597
00:35:39.420 --> 00:35:43.200
So I'm thinking, wouldn't it be nice if I'm able to

598
00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:43.560
actually

599
00:35:44.460 --> 00:35:48.120
measure this double-strand DNA molecule as a whole?

600
00:35:48.660 --> 00:35:52.150
That will change the fragmentomics field from 1D to

601
00:35:52.260 --> 00:35:52.740
2D.

602
00:35:53.920 --> 00:35:57.590
And I thought one way to do that is somehow you have a chain which

603
00:35:57.760 --> 00:36:01.540
link the two member of the gloves together.

604
00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.760
So what we did is develop a series of stem-loop primers,

605
00:36:05.740 --> 00:36:09.440
and then we attach onto the end, and the

606
00:36:09.480 --> 00:36:12.780
stem-loop length varies, depends on the length of the jacket

607
00:36:13.860 --> 00:36:16.820
edge, jacket ends, and then they are bar-coded.

608
00:36:17.920 --> 00:36:21.856
And then if it is perfect ligated, we have this basicallyA ring

609
00:36:21.896 --> 00:36:25.756
type of structure. If it's not, then we can digest it

610
00:36:25.796 --> 00:36:29.556
away with exonuclease. And then we can basically sequence this by

611
00:36:29.576 --> 00:36:30.876
Pacific Bioscience system.

612
00:36:33.756 --> 00:36:37.426
And now with this sort of structure, then we need a new type of nomenclature,

613
00:36:37.516 --> 00:36:41.276
because imagine now we have this two-dimensional double-strand

614
00:36:41.286 --> 00:36:45.256
DNA molecule in a circulation, which we can measure with four

615
00:36:45.336 --> 00:36:48.976
ends. And so we thought the one way is to do a

616
00:36:48.996 --> 00:36:52.866
nomenclature with this line, separate the two strand, the Watson strand and

617
00:36:52.916 --> 00:36:56.776
Crick strand, and the arrow is a five prime to three prime, and then can

618
00:36:56.796 --> 00:36:58.456
basically write the end motif that way.

619
00:36:59.265 --> 00:37:02.796
And by doing this, for example, we can say the sequence of the end motif

620
00:37:03.516 --> 00:37:07.256
or how many end motif you're looking at, so only one nucleotide, so

621
00:37:07.336 --> 00:37:10.876
one, one, one, one, et cetera. And there are many types of variations.

622
00:37:13.456 --> 00:37:15.816
And we call this holistic end motif analysis.

623
00:37:15.936 --> 00:37:19.916
An exciting thing about that is now many people are putting in this sort of

624
00:37:19.976 --> 00:37:22.856
sequencing data into foundation model to be trained.

625
00:37:23.316 --> 00:37:25.536
But normally, of course, you only have A, C, T, G.

626
00:37:26.016 --> 00:37:29.876
But now, suddenly with this concept, you have more than four possibility,

627
00:37:29.956 --> 00:37:33.056
because imagine if it's double-strand DNA, you can call it A, C, T, G.

628
00:37:33.516 --> 00:37:37.436
If one side is protruding, you can call it A prime, C prime, T prime, et

629
00:37:37.476 --> 00:37:41.296
cetera. If it's receding, then call it A double prime, T double prime, et

630
00:37:41.336 --> 00:37:45.296
cetera. So instead of having four possibility, A, C, T, G, you now have 12.

631
00:37:47.136 --> 00:37:50.776
And this, for example, by using just one from each of the end,

632
00:37:51.176 --> 00:37:54.816
we were able to actually separate the liver cancer and control from the

633
00:37:54.876 --> 00:37:55.876
plasma very well.

634
00:37:56.976 --> 00:38:00.336
And this is actually to show the combination from the usual

635
00:38:00.396 --> 00:38:03.036
EM5 all the way up to the one, one, one, one.

636
00:38:04.676 --> 00:38:08.396
And furthermore, this method is very efficient in terms of the number of molecules

637
00:38:08.456 --> 00:38:11.756
you need. You can see with a few thousand molecules, you already have over

638
00:38:11.856 --> 00:38:14.295
performance over what you have in the field.

639
00:38:15.536 --> 00:38:19.376
So finally, in conclusion, I hope I've convinced you circulating DNA analysis

640
00:38:19.756 --> 00:38:22.476
has created a number of paradigm shift in medical diagnostics.

641
00:38:23.056 --> 00:38:26.876
And one interesting thing is the similarities between pregnancy and cancer.

642
00:38:27.476 --> 00:38:31.296
And NIPT is already a standard of care in obstetrics and there are emerging

643
00:38:31.375 --> 00:38:33.056
applications in cancer screening.

644
00:38:33.616 --> 00:38:36.856
But more work is needed on fundamental biology like fragmentomics.

645
00:38:37.376 --> 00:38:40.326
So finally, I'd like to thank individual from my group for generating the results

646
00:38:40.336 --> 00:38:42.896
which are shown today, and thank you very much for your time.

647
00:38:46.136 --> 00:38:49.756
Thank you,

648
00:38:49.836 --> 00:38:52.856
Professor Lo. What an amazing story.

649
00:38:52.916 --> 00:38:55.156
I love how everything started and

